{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19102"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82615"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11836"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67781"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"1435"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5795"},{"type":"tags","id":"6352"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28244"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82615"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after rolling her ankle while playing netball one hour ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her right ankle is swollen and tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA decision is to be made as to whether to arrange an X-ray. The Ottawa Ankle Rules are a validated clinical decision tool used to determine whether ankle and foot X-rays are necessary following acute ankle injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"All the following are included in the Rules EXCEPT which one?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inability to weight bear for four steps","Tenderness at the base of the fifth metatarsal","Tenderness at the posterior edge of the lateral malleolus","Tenderness of the Achilles tendon","Tenderness over the navicular bone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Ottawa Ankle Rules have excellent sensitivity for detecting clinically significant fractures while reducing unnecessary imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness at the posterior edge of the lateral malleolus\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the key components of the Ottawa Ankle Rules. Tenderness along the posterior edge of either malleolus (lateral or medial) suggests the need for ankle X-rays.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness at the base of the fifth metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the midfoot assessment in the Ottawa Ankle Rules. This area is commonly injured in ankle inversion injuries and may indicate a Jones fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness over the navicular bone\u003C/strong\u003E is another component of the midfoot assessment in the Ottawa Rules. The navicular is an important weight-bearing bone in the midfoot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness of the Achilles tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the Ottawa Ankle Rules. While Achilles tendon injuries can occur with ankle trauma, assessment of the Achilles is not included in the decision-making for X-ray ordering according to these rules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to weight bear for four steps\u003C/strong\u003E is a crucial component of the Ottawa Rules. This is defined as inability to take four steps both immediately after the injury and in the Emergency Department.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Ottawa Ankle Rules state that ankle X-rays are only required if there is pain in the malleolar zone and either malleolar tenderness or inability to weight bear. Foot X-rays are only required if there is pain in the midfoot zone and either navicular or base of fifth metatarsal tenderness or inability to weight bear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Ottawa Ankle Rules include assessment of malleolar tenderness, navicular tenderness, base of fifth metatarsal tenderness, and ability to weight bear.","The Ottawa Ankle Rules have high sensitivity for detecting clinically significant ankle and midfoot fractures.","Inability to weight bear is defined as inability to take four steps immediately after the injury and in the emergency department."],"references":["Gomes et al. Diagnostic accuracy of the Ottawa ankle rule to exclude fractures in acute ankle injuries in adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis, BMC Musculoskeletal Disorders, 2022, https://bmcmusculoskeletdisord.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12891-022-05831-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67781"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67781"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T12:12:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T12:13:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11836"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"}